 leaving arrogance and untruthfulness further and further behind. The June weather was delicious. The sky was blue, the larks were soaring high  over the green corn, I thought all that countryside more beautiful and peaceful  by far than I had ever known The sky to be yet. Many pleasant pictures of the life  that I would lead there, and of the change for the better that would come over  my character when I had a guiding spirit at my side whose simple faith and  clear home wisdom I had proved, beguiled my way. They awakened a tender emotion  in me; for my heart was softened by my return, and such a change had come to  pass, that I felt like one who was toiling home barefoot from distant travel,  and whose wanderings had lasted many years. The schoolhouse where Biddy was mistress I had never seen; but, the little  roundabout lane by which I entered the village, for quietness' sake, took me  past it. I was disappointed to find that the day was a holiday; no children  were there, and Biddy's house was closed. Some hopeful notion of seeing her,  busily engaged in her daily duties, before her saw me, had been in my mind and  was defeated. But the forge was a very short distance off, and I went towards the forge under the  sweet green limes, listening for the clink of Joe's hammer. Long after I ought  to have heard it, and long after I had fancied I heard it and found it but a  fancy, all was still. the  sweet green limes were there, and the white thorns were there,  and the chestnut-trees were there, and the  sweet green limes leaves rustled harmoniously when I  stopped to listen; but, the clink of Joe's hammer Joe's hammer was not in the midsummer wind. Almost fearing, without knowing why, to come in view of the forge, I saw it at  last, and saw that it was closed. No gleam of fire, no glittering shower of  sparks, no roar of bellows; all shut up, and still. But Biddy's house was not deserted, and the best parlor seemed to be in use, for  there were white curtains fluttering in   window, and its window was open and  gay with flowers. I went softly towards its window, meaning to peep over the flowers,  when Joe and Biddy stood before me, arm in arm. At first Biddy gave a cry, as if Biddy thought it was my apparition, but in  another moment Biddy was in my embrace. I wept to see Biddy, and Biddy wept to see  me; I, because Biddy looked so fresh and pleasant; she, because I looked so worn  and white. "But Biddy, how smart you are!" "Yes, dear Pip." "And Joe, how smart you are!" "Yes, dear old Pip, old chap." I looked at both of them, from one to the other, and then— "It's my wedding-day!" cried Biddy, in a burst of happiness, "and I am married  to Joe!" both of them had taken me into the kitchen, and I had laid my head down on the old deal  table. Biddy held one of my hands to Biddy lips, and Joe's restoring touch was on  my shoulder. "Which he warn't strong enough, my dear, fur to be surprised,"  said Joe. And Biddy said, "I ought to have thought of it, JoeJoe, but I was  too happy." They were both so overjoyed to see me, so proud to see me, so  touched by my coming to They, so delighted that I should have come by accident  to make They day complete! My first thought was one of great thankfulness that I had never breathed this  last baffled hope to Joe. How often, while Joe was with me in my illness, had he was with me in my illness  risen to her lips! How irrevocable would have been Joe knowledge of he was with me in my illness, if Joe  had remained with me but another hour! "Biddy," said I, "you have the best husband in the whole world, and if you  could have seen Joe by my bed you would have—But no, you couldn't love Joe  better than you do." "No, I couldn't indeed," said Biddy. "And, JoeJoe, you have the best wife in the whole world, and Biddy will make  you as happy as even you deserve to be, you dear, good, noble Joe!" Joe looked at me with a quivering lip, and fairly put Joe sleeve before Joe  eyes. "And Joe and Biddy both, as